05231nam a22006735i 9780822396345DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19921992ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223963457 a10.1515/97808223963452doi  a(DE-B1597)553416  a(OCoLC)1226679850  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1995b.C537 1992 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/0122200aClassical Hollywood Narrative :bThe Paradigm Wars /cJane M. Gaines. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1992] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b10 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Family Melodrama of Classical Narrative Cinema -- tDickens. Griffith, and Film Theory Today -- tForm Wars: The Political Unconscious of Formalist Theory -- tFilm Response from Eye to I: The Kuleshov Experiment -- tSecuring the Fictional Narrative as a Tale of the Historical Real: The Return of Martin Guerre -- tBetween Melodrama and Realism: Anthony Asquith's Underaround and King Vidor's The Crowd -- tThe Hieroglyph and the Whore: D. W. Griffith's Intolerance -- tThe She-Man: Postmodern Bi-Sexed Performance in Film and Video -- tDead Ringer: Jacqueline Onassis and the Look-Alike -- tNostalgia for the Present -- tReading Dynasty: Television and Reception Theory -- tDialogues of the Living Dead -- tImage/Machine/Image: On the Use and Abuse of Marx and Metaphor in Television Theory -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the 1970s film studies has been dominated by a basic paradigm-the concept of classical Hollywood cinema-that is, the protagonist-driven narrative, valued for the way it achieves closure by neatly answering all of the enigmas it raises. It has been held to be a form so powerful that its aesthetic devices reinforce gender positions in society. In a variety of ways, the essays collected here-representing the work of some of the most innovative theorists writing today-challenge this paradigm.Significantly expanded from a special issue of South Atlantic Quarterly (Spring 1989), these essays confront the extent to which formalism has continued to dominate film theory, reexamine the role of melodrama in cinematic development, revise notions of "patriarchal cinema," and assert the importance of television and video to cinema studies. A range of topics are discussed, from the films of D. W. Griffith to sexuality in avant-garde film to television's Dynasty.Contributors. Rick Altman, Richard Dienst, Jane Feuer, Jane Gaines, Christine Gledhill, Miriam Hansen, Norman N. Holland, Fredric Jameson, Bill Nichols, Janey Staiger, Chris Straayer, John O. Thompson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aMotion picturesxPhilosophy. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspects. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aNichols, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStraayer, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGledhill, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJameson, Fredric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaines, Jane M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFeuer, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaines, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStaiBer, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansen, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Norman, econtributor.4